1. What is a Pod Disruption?

A disruption is any event that makes a Pod unavailable.

Examples

Pod Deleted
Node Reboot
Cluster Upgrade
Autoscaler removes node
Node Failure
Disk Failure
Memory Pressure

Not every disruption is bad.

Many disruptions are expected.

Example:

Cluster Upgrade

Node1
 ┌───────────────┐
 │ nginx Pod     │
 └───────────────┘

Administrator

kubectl drain node1

↓

Pod moved to Node2

Application still available
2. Types of Disruptions

There are two categories.

                 Disruptions
                      │
         ┌────────────┴────────────┐
         │                         │
 Voluntary                 Involuntary
Voluntary Disruptions

These are intentional.

Examples

✅ Node Upgrade

kubectl drain worker01

✅ Cluster Autoscaler

Remove unused node

✅ Deployment Update

kubectl rollout restart deployment nginx

✅ Administrator deletes pod

kubectl delete pod nginx
Involuntary Disruptions

Unexpected.

Examples

❌ Node crashes

Power Failure

❌ Disk Failure

❌ Kernel Panic

❌ Network Partition

❌ Node OOM

❌ Cloud VM disappears

These cannot be prevented by PDBs, although they still count against the disruption budget.

3. Why Pod Disruptions Matter

Suppose your application has

Replicas = 3
Node1     Node2     Node3

PodA      PodB      PodC

If administrator upgrades Node1

Without PDB

Node1 drained

PodA deleted

Available Pods = 2

Now immediately drain Node2

PodB deleted

Only PodC left

Application overloaded

This can cause downtime.

4. PodDisruptionBudget (PDB)

PDB tells Kubernetes

Never allow more than X Pods to be unavailable during voluntary disruptions.

Think of it as

Application says

"I need at least 2 Pods alive."

Kubernetes obeys.

5. How PDB Works

Suppose

Deployment

Replicas = 5

PDB

minAvailable = 4

Current Pods

Pod1 Ready

Pod2 Ready

Pod3 Ready

Pod4 Ready

Pod5 Ready

Drain node

↓

One Pod removed

Ready Pods = 4

Allowed

Try removing another

Ready Pods = 3

Blocked

Drain waits

Exactly how the Eviction API behaves when respecting the PDB.

